To clarify which assumptions lead to such simple expressions for the spine-fan reconnection [Eqs. (19, 21)], we first note that we separately treated the ribbon motions in the two domains, DÂ±\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$D^\pm$$\end{document}, but did not explicitly introduce the asymmetric location of the current sheet into the formulation. In reality, a current sheet resides on one side of the fan causing expansion of CR on that side and contraction on the other (see, for 3D simulation results, Fig.Â 9). Another important element missing in our formulation is the geometry of the current sheet lying between the interacting spine and fan (Fig.Â 5e). We simply treated it as a small ring around the null. As a result, this energy conversion rate [Eq. (21)] does not contain a dimensionless parameter representing the current sheet geometry, unlike that of 2D X-point reconnection [Eq. (8)] and torsional reconnection [Eq. (16)]. A more rigorous formulation is underway, but in the present paper, we limit the scope of investigation to the average effect of the spine-fan reconnection on the positional shift of CR.

